Principle Component Analysis¶

First, since the output data has too many attributes, meaning too many number of frequency values that magnitude output is measured for, to simplfy the process a dimensionality reduction should be applied. Principle component analysis is applied to the output data for reducing the number of attributes required to understand the data. This has done by appling PCA for magnitude of S11, real part of S11 and imaginary part of S11 seperatly in the following parts.

PCA for Output Data¶

1) PCA for Magnitude of S11¶

First of all PCA is applied to the magnitude of S11 with following command.

The above results show that with only PC1 it is possible to explain 60% of the variance of the data. Which is a good result that shows most of the variance of the data can be explained with PC1.

Then, to see visually how much variance is explained by each principle component scree plot is plotted:

In [13]:
# scree plot of variance

        addlabels=TRUE)

The above plot shows that there is a significant different between PC1 and other principle components in explaining the variance within the data. When we use both PC1 and PC2 the explained variance increases to 72.2%, which can also be preferred for later measurements. However, PC1 alone is already a good component to express the data.

Understanding How Good Can the Principle Components of Input Data Explain Output Data:¶

Correlation Between Input Data and Real Part of Output Data:¶

In order to understand that the correlation between each principle component of input_data and each principle component of s11_real, a correlation matrix is generated and each pair having correlation above 0.8 is printed below.

In [24]:
# extract scores from the PCA results
input_scores <- input_data_pca$x  
output_scores_real <- s11_real_pca$x 

# calculate correlations between all pairs of PCs
num_input_pcs <- ncol(input_scores)
num_output_pcs <- ncol(output_scores_real)
cor_matrix <- matrix(NA, nrow = num_input_pcs, ncol = num_output_pcs,
                     dimnames = list(paste0("Input_PC", 1:num_input_pcs),
                                     paste0("Real_Output_PC", 1:num_output_pcs)))

# fill the matrix with correlations
for (i in 1:num_input_pcs) {
  for (j in 1:num_output_pcs) {
    cor_matrix[i, j] <- cor(input_scores[, i], output_scores_real[, j])
  }
}

# pairs with high correlations treshold = 0.8
high_cor_pairs <- which(abs(cor_matrix) > 0.8, arr.ind = TRUE)

# display high-correlation pairs with their correlation values
if (nrow(high_cor_pairs) > 0) {
  for (k in 1:nrow(high_cor_pairs)) {
    input_pc <- high_cor_pairs[k, 1]
    output_pc <- high_cor_pairs[k, 2]
    correlation_value <- cor_matrix[input_pc, output_pc]
    cat(sprintf("Input_PC%d and Real_Output_PC%d have a high correlation of %.2f\n",
                input_pc, output_pc, correlation_value))
  }
} else {
  cat("No pairs with high correlation found.\n")
}

Input_PC1 and Real_Output_PC1 have a high correlation of 0.92

The above result shows that there is only "high correlation" between PC1 of Input Data and PC1 of real part of output data. Since previously, we showed that PC1 for real part of output data is good to explain the variance between data and now we can see the high correlation between PC1 of input data with that output data, we can conclude that PC1 of input data can explain the real part of output data very well.

What insights can we draw from the PCA regarding the relationship between geometry and electromagnetic behavior?¶

We need to determine what are the attributes that most contribute to the PC1 of input_data.

In [55]:
loadings_input <- input_data_pca$rotation

loadings_input_pc1 <- loadings_input[, 1]

sorted_loadings_pc1 <- sort(abs(loadings_input_pc1), decreasing = TRUE)

top_features <- names(sorted_loadings_pc1)[1:5]
print(top_features)

[1] "width.of.patch"                   "height.of.substrate"             
[3] "dielectric.constant.of.substrate" "length.of.patch"                 
[5] "height.of.patch"

The PCA results suggest that the features contributing most to the variance in the data are the width of the patch, height of the substrate, dielectric constant of the substrate, length of the patch, and height of the patch. These top features are likely influential in shaping the relationship between the geometric properties of the design and its electromagnetic behavior. Therefore, they highlight key dimensions and material properties (like dielectric constant) that impact overall performance. This insight provides an understanding how specific geometric adjustments might alter electromagnetic responses.

Regression Modelling¶

First, we need to select for which frequency values we should make predictions for. To do that we can determine the resonance frequencies where magnitude of S11 is the lowest.

To Find Resonance Frequencies:¶

With the below command, for each sample the frequency where the lowest magnitude occured is obtained. And then, count of frequency with lowest magnitudes is found. Below "resonance frequencies" shows the top 3 frequency values where the lowest magnitude is obtained more frequently.

In [28]:
# Find the frequency index where the S11 magnitude is minimum
min_magnitude_indices <- apply(s11_magnitude, 1, which.min)

# Extract the frequencies corresponding to the minimum S11 magnitude for each frequency band
resonance_frequencies <- colnames(s11_magnitude)[min_magnitude_indices]


#print(resonance_frequencies)

# Count the frequency of each resonance frequency
resonance_frequency_count <- table(resonance_frequencies)

#print(resonance_frequency_count)

# Sort the count in descending order and get the top 3
top_3_resonance_frequencies <- sort(resonance_frequency_count, decreasing = TRUE)[1:3]

# Print the top 3 resonance frequencies
print(top_3_resonance_frequencies)

# Plot the distribution of resonance frequencies
barplot(table(resonance_frequencies), 
        main = "Distribution of Resonance Frequencies", 
        xlab = "Frequency Labels", 
        ylab = "Count", 
        col = "skyblue", 
        las = 2)  # Rotate x-axis labels for readability

resonance_frequencies

  77   63    6

Model Performance and Interpretability¶

Model Performance and Interpretability

  1. PCA vs. Regression Models for Simplifying and Predicting Performance

    • PCA helps reduce the complexity of the data by identifying the principal components, which capture the most variance with fewer features. In the context of antenna performance, PCA can simplify complex datasets involving multiple geometric and material parameters, allowing us to work with fewer components that still capture the majority of the datas information.
    • Regression Models take this simplification further by mapping the reduced-dimensional data directly to the antenna performance metrics, like gain, bandwidth, or efficiency. Regression models, especially if linear, can offer interpretable relationships by showing how each principal component or feature impacts the performance metric. However, they may fall short in capturing non-linear interactions, which are often inherent in electromagnetic behavior.

  2. Potential Limitations and Improvements

    • Limitations:
      • PCA assumes linear relationships among features, which may oversimplify the data, missing out on crucial non-linear interactions between geometry and electromagnetic properties.
      • Linear regression models based on principal components may not fully capture complex, non-linear behaviors typical in antenna performance, especially under varying environmental conditions or material properties.
    • Improvements:
      • Non-linear dimensionality reduction techniques, like kernel PCA, could capture more complex relationships.
      • Non-linear regression methods, such as polynomial regression, random forests, or neural networks, may improve predictive accuracy by modeling interactions that linear models miss.

Using these methods to enhance PCA and regression models could yield a better balance between interpretability and the ability to capture the nuanced, non-linear aspects of antenna performance.
